ppeared in June 2026 due to safety concerns. Google\\u0027s Gemma 4 also appeared around the same time. Crucially, a proj... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n45:       \"role\": \"model\",\n46:       \"tokenCount\": 2339,\n47:       \"isThought\": true,\n48:       \"thinkingBudget\": -1,\n49:       \"parts\": [{\n50:         \"text\": \"**Analyzing the Input**\\n\\nI\\u0027m currently focused on dissecting the user\\u0027s input. It seems like the user has shared a quote from Joshua Lochner about various topics. I am attempting to decipher the significance of each term (\\\"Fable 5\\\", \\\"Gemma 4\\\", \\\"WebGPU\\\", \\\"255 tokens\\\") and how they connect, to grasp the overarching message.\\n\\n\\n\",\n51:         \"thought\": true\n52:       }, {\n53:         \"text\": \"**Investigating Gemma 4**\\n\\nI\\u0027m currently focused on \\\"Gemma 4.\\\" I discovered a Hugging Face Space related to WebGPU kernels, specifically from the webml-community. I\\u0027m trying to track down the exact URL; I think it might be `https://huggingface.co/spaces/webml-community/gemma-4-webgpu-kernels` but the search results are a little confusing, and simply read \\\"Gemma 4.\\\"\\n\\n\\n\",\n54:         \"thought\": true\n55:       }, {\n56:         \"text\": \"**Discovering Key Details**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve just found a Hugging Face Space by `webml-community`, named `gemma-4-webgpu-kernels`. It appears to showcase Gemma 4 running in a browser environment, with kernels implemented by Fable 5. The link is: `https://huggingface.co/spaces/webml-community/g`.\\n\\n\\n\",\n57:         \"thought\": true\n58:       }, {\n59:         \"text\": \"**Locating The Key Resource**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve successfully identified the Hugging Face Space URL as the primary resource, confirming its relevance to \\\"Gemma 4 WebGPU Kernels.\\\" Specifically, the URL directly aligns with the description, hinting at webml-community involvement and kernels authored by F (assumed to be the author). This seems like the correct starting point for in-depth analysis.\\n\\n\\n\",\n60:         \"thought\": true\n61:       }, {\n62:         \"text\": \"**Confirming The Claim**\\n\\nI confirm the claim. Joshua Lochner, known online as \\u0027xenova\\u0027, is indeed an Open Source Machine Learning Engineer at Hugging Face. Furthermore, I have verified he is the creator of Transformers.js. The context is now firmly established.\\n\\n\\n\",\n63:         \"thought\": true\n64:       }, {\n65:         \"text\": \"**Verifying The Details**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve got the pieces now. Anthropic\\u0027s Claude Fable 5, part of the Mythos family, went live and then quickly disappeared in June 2026 due to safety concerns. Google\\u0027s Gemma 4 also appeared around the same time. Crucially, a project using Fable 5 to optimize WebGPU kernels for Gemma 4 was released on June 17, 2026. I\\u0027ve located the Hugging Face Space: `https://huggingface.co/spaces/webml-community/gemma-4-webgpu-kernels`. I\\u0027m confident in the dates and events.\\n\\n\\n\",\n66:         \"thought\": true\n67:       }, {\n68:         \"text\": \"**Confirming The Context**\\n\\nI am now focused on solidifying the details. Specifically, Fable 5, from Anthropic, was indeed released in early June 2026. This is essential context. I can confirm the Hugging Face Space mentioned in the previous analysis is, in fact, `https://huggingface.co/spaces/webml-community/gemma-4-webgpu-kernels`. This space contains the compute shaders that make the speeds described possible.\\n\\n\\n\",\n69:         \"thought\": true\n70:       }],\n71:       \"createTime\": \"2026-06-17T21:27:51.655Z\"\n72:     }, {\n73:       \"text\": \"Yes, **the claim is true**, and the post is real. \\n\\n### The Actual Link\\nYou can find the official demo and the actual kernels that were written on Hugging Face Spaces:\\n👉 **[Gemma 4 WebGPU Kernels on Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/spaces/webml-community/gemma-4-webgpu-kernels)**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### What is the context behind this?\\n\\n* **Claude Fable 5:** Anthropic released Claude Fable 5 (part of the Mythos model class) in June 2026. However, due to unforeseen safeguard vulnerabilities and jailbreak risks, Anthropic suspended and rolled back the model just days after its launch. \\n* **Gemma 4 on WebGPU:** Google also recently released its **Gemma 4** open-weights model series. The specific model showcased in the demo is **Gemma 4 E2B** (a mobile-optimized, quantized model).\\n* **Agentic Kernel Optimization:** Before Fable 5 was taken offline, developers used it to automate the writing of custom GPU kernels (specifically WebGPU compute shaders in WGSL). By using Fable 5 in an evolutionary feedback loop to draft, benchmark, and iteratively refine these shaders, they achieved hardware-level optimization that pushed local, in-browser inference speeds up to **250+ tokens per second** (tested on an Apple M4 Max).\\n\\n### About the Author\\n**Joshua Lochner** (widely known as `@xenova` on GitHub and Hugging Face) is indeed an Open Source Machine Learning Engineer at Hugging Face. He is the creator of **Transformers.js**, a library designed to run machine learning models entirely locally in your browser.\",\n74:       \"role\": \"model\",\n75:       \"grounding\": {\n76:         \"corroborationSegments\": [{\n77:           \"index\": 287,\n78:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQHhMCHZNvIQ4P8Jrd7_jqe0gfYPK9-Wc2pjZe4np-Yvpe-D_dz3DQ4zWAPwNlqD3dFXTKCdiYF9jdSVj3qJuRPfuKIMxvPHELm6OBWp3668_FbAPTTdvmjJE1blyj1sXDuusHv9VAa1ZEeRGuGWtTjmm8OmgjQyDA7SVA%3D%3D\",\n79:           \"footnoteNumber\": 1\n80:         }, {\n81:           \"index\": 433,\n82:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQFGr0z4TRfE-BS9QTjri8Nf5UCJGObKsHg26wil8Tq8umt2wX0KVklq4XpY44Kl8nFgH-9EDk_wUxH