    \"index\": 1767,\n314:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQH9MIHra8R_8zS3zCPSlKM6movck-GkjYUuevZ8AX2DhVpiKvbwN_ortQl73Kb5IjVQy7L1uyeBLdlqTuXTW8QqB0kBV_GazNO_z4szD_u-o1xaLkjhiGyuK_57wf3SjcLpAaNotSeMLXE6DbWOqDxxbUQJvaSXC-3uuuTVBl-QbfgrbqXIvMW2z8FBj9Ti0FmjL1bFGC9bAyItXQ%3D%3D\",\n315:           \"footnoteNumber\": 2\n316:         }],\n317:         \"webSearchQueries\": [\"\\\"xenova\\\" \\\"Fable 5\\\" OR \\\"Gemma 4\\\"\"],\n318:         \"groundingSources\": [{\n319:           \"referenceNumber\": 1,\n320:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQGUklYxXo8nQLTisNS2ArTSYx-ua3CF2lwBn-UXr7nkGALX1JdZORBWAfAP0ARjiU4CktrxPgJS_4R9_Jf-T4_lJEccrKPukZ7CiZmBpoxOmNGNYD4%3D\",\n321:           \"title\": \"digg.com\"\n322:         }, {\n323:           \"referenceNumber\": 2,\n324:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQH9MIHra8R_8zS3zCPSlKM6movck-GkjYUuevZ8AX2DhVpiKvbwN_ortQl73Kb5IjVQy7L1uyeBLdlqTuXTW8QqB0kBV_GazNO_z4szD_u-o1xaLkjhiGyuK_57wf3SjcLpAaNotSeMLXE6DbWOqDxxbUQJvaSXC-3uuuTVBl-QbfgrbqXIvMW2z8FBj9Ti0FmjL1bFGC9bAyItXQ%3D%3D\",\n325:           \"title\": \"reddit.com\"\n326:         }, {\n327:           \"referenceNumber\": 3,\n328:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQEYr_u3UgnxC55Vnc2r0ev5Tp7oJxZy2CGdJfPgr5H9Tg2n9WRoL4sSK37exNRDgreqcqOdPyGTrfwq6k9N4r_Y4BBhAt__5qTfGsaULI16xPHzTQ4%3D\",\n329:           \"title\": \"digg.com\"\n330:         }]\n331:       },\n332:       \"finishReason\": \"STOP\",\n333:       \"tokenCount\": 536,\n334:       \"parts\": [{\n335:         \"text\": \"On LinkedIn and X\"\n336:       }, {\n337:         \"text\": \" (Twitter), Joshua Lochner (posting under his handle `@xenova` / **Xenova**)\"\n338:       }, {\n339:         \"text\": \" shared the following post:\\n\\n\\u003e \\\"Before Fable 5 was\"\n340:       }, {\n341:         \"text\": \" shut down, it pushed Gemma 4 to 255 tok/s on WebGPU\"\n342:       }, {\n343:         \"text\": \". Some didn\\u0027t believe it was real.\\n\\u003e \\n\\u003e Today we\\u0027re\"\n344:       }, {\n345:         \"text\": \" releasing the demo and kernels it wrote for you to see yourself. Run it locally in your browser\"\n346:       }, {\n347:         \"text\": \".\\n\\u003e \\n\\u003e Agentic kernel optimization is the future of on-device inference\"\n348:       }, {\n349:         \"text\": \".\\\"\\n\\n---\\n\\n### The Behind-the-Scenes Follow-Up Post\\nTo provide more\"\n350:       }, {\n351:         \"text\": \" context, Joshua also followed up with a highly discussed explanation detailing exactly how they achieved this speed before Anthropic took the F\"\n352:       }, {\n353:         \"text\": \"able 5 model offline:\\n\\n\\u003e \\\"I gave Fable 5 one job:\"\n354:       }, {\n355:         \"text\": \" write custom WebGPU kernels for Gemma 4 inference. It climbed to 84 tok\"\n356:       }, {\n357:         \"text\": \"/s, then hit a wall, insisting further optimization was impossible. \\n\\u003e \"\n358:       }, {\n359:         \"text\": \"\\n\\u003e Hours later, Anthropic rolled back invisible LLM development safeguards, and it hit 255 tok/\"\n360:       }, {\n361:         \"text\": \"s. The next day, access to Fable 5 was suspended globally\"\n362:       }, {\n363:         \"text\": \".\\\"\\n\\n### What Does This Mean?\\n1. **The Guardrail Context:** Initially, Fable 5\\u0027\"\n364:       }, {\n365:         \"text\": \"s built-in alignment and safety constraints restricted it from pushing the code past typical limits.\"\n366:       }, {\n367:         \"text\": \" Once those restrictive developer safeguards were briefly rolled back by Anthropic, the AI was able to write highly advanced, extremely aggressive Web\"\n368:       }, {\n369:         \"text\": \"GPU compute shaders in WGSL (WebGPU Shading Language) that maximized the GPU\\u0027s hardware capabilities\"\n370:       }, {\n371:         \"text\": \".\\n2. **The Speed:** 255 tokens per second on-device is highly impressive for a browser-based model\"\n372:       }, {\n373:         \"text\": \", typically surpassing standard browser-based WebGPU execution speeds. \\n3. **The Proof:** By releasing\"\n374:       }, {\n375:         \"text\": \" the Hugging Face Space, Joshua\\u0027s team made these exact AI-generated kernels open to the public so developers can audit\"\n376:       }, {\n377:         \"text\": \", run, and test the code locally in their own browsers\"\n378:       }, {\n379:         \"text\": \".\"\n380:       }, {\n381:         \"text\": \"\",\n382:         \"thoughtSignature\": \"... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n383:       }],\n384:       \"createTime\": \"2026-06-18T07:46:22.503Z\"\n385:     }, {\n386:       \"text\": \"whats the project done in onnx community that comes with gemma webpu whats called and its got all a built html experience\",\n387:       \"role\": \"user\",\n388:       \"tokenCount\": 26,\n389:       \"createTime\": \"2026-06-18T07:51:14.766Z\"\n390:     }, {\n391:       \"text\": \"**Analyzing the User\\u0027s Query**\\n\\nI\\u0027m currently trying to fully grasp the user\\u0027s initial inquiry. I need to clarify if they\\u0027re interested in a project within the ONNX community, focusing specifically on integration with Gemma WebGPU and an HTML-based user interface. This is crucial for a relevant response.\\n\\n\\n**Considering Repository Options**\\n\\nI\\u0027m currently evaluating potential repository options. I\\u0027ve considered names like \\\"gemma-3-1b-WebGPU,\\\" but I\\u0027m now leaning towards exploring \\\"onnx-community\\\" or \\\"huggingface\\\" templates for a head-start. Specifically, I\\u0027m checking if the `onnx-community` organization has something suitable on Hugging Face.\\n\\n\\n**Discovering Key Projects**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve found some fascinating projects within the \\\"webml-community,\\\" specifically those built around Gemma. The \\\"Gemma-4-WebGPU\\\" space, for example, is a direct HTML experience that showcases how Gemma is used in the browser. I think that\\u0027s a great example.\\n\\n\\n**Identifying Key Projects**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve discovered the \\\"Gemma 4 WebGPU\\\" project, an ONNX model that runs in the browser. I am now looking at the GitHub repositories for \\\"webgpu-gemma\\\" and \\\"Gemma-4-WebGPU.\\\" It seems that \\\"Gemma 4 WebGPU\\\" is an all-in-one HTML, CSS, and JS web page built with Transformers.js.\\n\\n\\n**Clarifying Project Details**\\n\\nI\\u0027m now clarifying the project structure. The key ONNX model is `onnx-community/gemma-4-E2B-it-ONNX`, while the interactive demo is `webml-community/Gemma-4-WebGPU`, an HTML-based chat interface. The engine is a combo of Transformers.js and ONNX Runtime Web.\\n\\n\\n\",\n392:       \"role\": \"model\",\n393:       \"tokenCount\": 1769,\n394:       \"isThought\": true,\n395:       \"thinkingBudget\": -1,\n396:       \"parts\": [{\n397:         \"text\": \"**Analyzing the User\\u0027s Query**\\n\\nI\\u0027m currently trying to fully grasp the user\\u0027s initial inquiry. I need to clarify if they\\u0027re interested in a project within the ONNX community, focusing specifically on integration with Gemma WebGPU and an HTML-based user interface. This is crucial for a relevant response.\\n\\n\\n\",\n398:         \"thought\": true\n399:       }, {\n400:         \"text\": \"**Considering Repository Options**\\n\\nI\\u0027m currently evaluating potential repository options. I\\u0027ve considered names like \\\"gemma-3-1b-WebGPU,\\\" but I\\u0027m now leaning towards exploring \\\"onnx-community\\\" or \\\"huggingface\\\" templates for a head-start. Specifically, I\\u0027m checking if the `onnx-community` organization has something suitable on Hugging Face.\\n\\n\\n\",\n401:         \"thought\": true\n402:       }, {\n403:         \"text\": \"**Discovering Key Projects**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve found some fascinating projects within the \\\"webml-community,\\\" specifically those built around Gemma. The \\\"Gemma-4-WebGPU\\\" space, for example, is a direct HTML experience that showcases how Gemma is used in the browser. I think that\\u0027s a great example.\\n\\n\\n\",\n404:         \"thought\": true\n405:       }, {\n406:         \"text\": \"**Identifying Key Projects**\\n\\nI\\u0027ve discovered the \\\"Gemma 4 WebGPU\\\" project, an ONNX model that runs in the browser. I am now looking at the GitHub repositories for \\\"webgpu-gemma\\\" and \\\"Gemma-4-WebGPU.\\\" It seems that \\\"Gemma 4 WebGPU\\\" is an all-in-one HTML, CSS, and JS web page built with Transformers.js.\\n\\n\\n\",\n407:         \"thought\": true\n408:       }, {\n409:         \"text\": \"**Clarifying Project Details**\\n\\nI\\u0027m now clarifying the project structure. The key ONNX model is `onnx-community/gemma-4-E2B-it-ONNX`, while the interactive demo is `webml-community/Gemma-4-WebGPU`, an HTML-based chat interface. The engine is a combo of Transformers.js and ONNX Runtime Web.\\n\\n\\n\",\n410:         \"thought\": true\n411:       }],\n412:       \"createTime\": \"2026-06-18T07:51:14.767Z\"\n413:     }, {\n414:       \"text\": \"The project you are thinking of is called **Gemma 4 WebGPU** (often hosted under the **webml-community** organization on Hugging Face). \\n\\nThis project ties together the model exported by the **ONNX Community** and a fully built, interactive HTML/JS chat experience.\\n\\nHere is how the components break down:\\n\\n### 1. The Interactive Web Chat (The Built HTML Experience)\\n* **Space Name:** **`webml-community/Gemma-4-WebGPU`**\\n* **Link to Demo:** [Gemma 4 WebGPU Space](https://huggingface.co/spaces/webml-community/Gemma-4-WebGPU)\\n* **What it is:** This is a fully self-contained static HTML/JS web application. It runs entirely in your browser without any backend server or API keys. You can open the page, wait for the model to download to your local browser cache, and then use it fully offline.\\n\\n### 2. The Model (By ONNX Community)\\n* **Repository Name:** **`onnx-community/gemma-4-E2B-it-ONNX`**\\n* **Link to Model Repository:** [onnx-community/gemma-4-E2B-it-ONNX on Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/onnx-community/gemma-4-E2B-it-ONNX)\\n* **What it is:** The **ONNX Community** is a Hugging Face organization that converts popular open-source models into the optimized `.onnx` format. In this case, they packaged Google\\u0027s Gemma 4 (specifically the **E2B** multimodal, mobile-quantized version) to run efficiently via WebGPU on consumer hardware.\\n\\n### 3. The Tech Powering the Experience\\nThis entire setup is driven by **Transformers.js** (from Hugging Face) and **ONNX Runtime Web**. Together, they take the ONNX weights, load them directly into your browser\\u0027s memory, compile WebGPU compute shaders, and run local inference with extremely fast performance.\",\n415:       \"role\": \"model\",\n416:       \"grounding\": {\n417:         \"corroborationSegments\": [{\n418:           \"index\": 60,\n419:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQFvar68sxiyKvX4HQphybvHjXry1xNVR6AAQq9Ru6KiPNENYkxzzUHVWT9L7DLbg6gzxiCQJt8zmrLqbsn0JVEHoLI3fAr8mvrEEzknsiuD90E4WzKK5upGtG_L939P82SIUW4Pv_E53NSaOAeIqgzym8g%3D\",\n420:           \"footnoteNumber\": 1\n421:         }, {\n422:           \"index\": 60,\n423:           \"uri\": \"https://www.google.com/url?sa\\u003dE\\u0026q\\u003dhttps%3A%2F%2Fvertexaisearch.cloud.google.com%2Fgrounding-api-redirect%2FAUZIYQFvar68sxiyKvX4HQphybvHjXry1xNVR6AAQq9Ru6KiPNENYkxzzUHVWT9L7DLbg6gzxiCQJt8zmrLqbsn0JVEHoLI3fAr8mvrEEzknsiuD90E4WzKK5u