    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The session messages are not stored locally in a file that I can easily find. They might be:\n1. Stored in the SQLite DB but I need a proper tool to read it\n2. Stored in the Nexus database (which is binary)\n3. Stored in a remote server (since this is a cloud-based service)\n4. Stored in the OpenCode process memory\n\nLooking at the logs, I can see that `session_messages` is a table in the SQLite DB. But when I searched for the session ID in the sqlite.db, I didn't find it. This could mean:\n- The messages for this session are stored in the Nexus database\n\n\n- The messages are streamed in real-time and not persisted locally\n- The session data directory contains the actual storage\n\nLet me check the OpenCode configuration to see if there's a specific database file or storage mechanism being used. Looking at the logs, the OpenCode process is spawned by the Mavis daemon and runs separately, so the conversation messages might be stored in the OpenCode process's own data files rather than in the Mavis sqlite database.\n\nI'm realizing that in this architecture, the daemon acts as the router while OpenCode handles the actual LLM calls, meaning the conversation history is likely maintained by OpenCode itself or stored elsewhere entirely. Let me try using the mavis CLI to query the session directly and see what message storage mechanisms are available.",
      "timestamp": 1781848296463
    },
