      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Excellent! I can now see the full session message structure! The `mavis session messages` command gave me the complete conversation in a well-structured JSON format. The schema is:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"msg_id\": \"msg_ede6e31ec001p1pc6OeJuZfW2C\",\n  \"role\": \"assistant\",\n  \"msg_type\": 2,\n  \"timestamp\": 1781848240376,\n  \"thinking_content\": \"...\",\n  \"msg_content\": \"...\",\n  \"tool_calls\": [...],\n  \"finish_reason\": \"tool-calls\",\n  \"usage\": {\n    \"total_tokens\": 67581,\n    \"context_window\": 200000\n  },\n  \"source\": \"api\"\n}\n```\n\nSo this is how Mavis stores its conversations. Now I want to understand the full storage architecture and export this session to a file. The key insight is that the session ID is `mvs_54b5193807c44930852f615d9ba50aad`, and the messages are stored in SQLite. I'm also noticing the `session_messages` table has `session_id`, `msg_id`, `role`, and `data` fields, though I need to figure out what the actual `data` field contains since my queries haven't returned results yet.\n\nLooking at the mavis output more carefully, I see the messages are actually being returned with fields like `msg_content`, `thinking_content`, `tool_calls`, and `finish_reason` — so the `data` column might be JSON or something different. The architecture seems to use a SQLite database (`C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.mavis\\sqlite.db`) with tables for sessions, session_messages, and other metadata. My search for the session ID in the SQLite file came up empty, which suggests either the data is stored elsewhere or the table structure is different than expected. I'm noticing the nexus database isn't being stored locally—the session_id doesn't appear in the sqlite.db file, which suggests the conversation data is actually flowing through MiniMax's servers rather than being persisted locally. The API responses include a source field, confirming these messages are fetched from a remote API endpoint. I'm noticing the Nexus database has WAL and SHM files alongside it, which suggests SQLite under the hood—the session_id probably isn't showing up in my hex search because those writes might be in the WAL file rather than the main database. Rather than keep digging through the database forensics, I should write a Node.js script using sql.js to properly query the session_messages table and confirm whether the current session's messages are actually stored locally or if they're coming from the API. The nexus database is likely a local cache mirroring server-side data, which explains why the session ID isn't in the sqlite.db file. Rather than dig through the database forensics, I should just write a Node.js script to query the session_messages table directly and see what's actually stored there. I can export the session to a readable format using a command like `mavis session export`.",
      "timestamp": 1781848328344
