      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Our export is **35.3 KB** for 33 messages in Mavis's clean format.\n\nIf stored in the Gemini JSON style, here's the overhead multiplication:\n\n| Layer | Mavis (actual) | Gemini equivalent |\n|---|---|---|\n| Per message | `content` + `role` + `timestamp` | Gemini adds `parts[]` (6–8 fragments), `thoughtSignature` (big base64 blob), `isThought`, `thinkingBudget`, `tokenCount`, `createTime` |\n| Per model response | `usage` object | Gemini adds `grounding` object with 10–20 `corroborationSegments` (full URLs), `webSearchQueries[]`, `groundingSources[]` |\n| Global | session-level metadata | `runSettings`, `systemInstruction` |\n\nA single complex Gemini response (like that Fable 5 one with the 2,000-char truncated thoughtSignature) was probably **15–20 KB on its own** for just one model turn. Our whole 33-message export in Mavis is 35 KB.\n\nSo if this conversation were exported in the Gemini format? Realistically **500 KB to 2 MB** — 15–50x bigger. And if one of our responses had a long chain-of-thought trace and web search grounding, that *one* message alone could rival our entire export's file size.\n\nThat's the difference between storing data for **operational use** (Mavis — lean, queryable, indexed) vs. storing data for **audit/compliance/debugging** (Gemini — everything including the kitchen sink, every URL traced, every thought fragment preserved).",
      "timestamp": 1781848584801
