    {
      "type": "answer",
      "text": "\nOh, `.mavis` isn't a format — it's just the **name of the directory**. It starts with a dot because on Mac/Linux that means \"hidden system folder,\" and it carried that convention over to Windows even though dots don't hide folders on Windows.\n\nIt's basically the equivalent of:\n- `~/.config/` on Linux\n- `~/Library/Application Support/` on macOS\n\nIt's the **data directory** where MiniMax Code stores all its working files — the SQLite database, session history, logs, skills, memory, MCP config, etc.\n\nSo the full path is:\n```\nC:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.mavis\\\n```\n\nWhich contains things like `sqlite.db`, `sessions/`, `logs/`, `memory/`, `agents/`, etc.\n\nYou could compare it to how:\n- VS Code stores settings in `AppData/Code/`\n- Chrome stores its profile in `AppData/Local/Google/Chrome/`\n- Discord stores data in `AppData/discord/`\n\nSame concept — a named application data folder, just with a dot in front because that's the convention the developers used.",
      "timestamp": 1781848861495
    },
    {
      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The user is asking about the `.mavis` data directory and what format it's in. They're asking: \"which is formatted .mavis?\" - I think they want to know what format the `.mavis` data directory is organized in, or what the `.mavis` directory structure looks like and what format the data is stored in.\n\nLet me explain: `.mavis` is just a directory name (it starts with a dot, which on Linux/macOS means it's a hidden directory). On Windows, dots in directory names are perfectly normal. So `C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.mavis` is just a folder called `.mavis` in the user's home directory.",
